            <h2>Additional Verb Forms Overview</h2>
            <p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">I</span>n this module you've gained a more complete picture of Old English
                verbs, as well as their relationship to modern English. We may not have an inflected infinitive any more, but our present
                and past participles can be mapped onto their Old English ancestors which were used in some of the same ways, our modal 
                verbs are directly descended from Old English forms, and  
                many prefixed verbs - from unlock, to outlie - can be seen to have evolved from Old English prefixed verbs.</p>
            <h3>Modal Auxiliaries</h3>
            <p>Modal Auxiliaires are a particular class of auxiliary (or 'helping') verb that is used to express necessity, possibility, 
                intention, permission, or ability. They are mostly preterite present verbs, and in many cases both their past and present form 
                can be recognised in modern English modals such as 'can' and 'could', 'shall' and 'should', and 'will' and 'would'. Often,
                the verb they 'help' goes to the end of the sentence, as in '<em>Ic can eow stæfcræft læran - I can teach you grammar</em>'.
                </p>
