            <h3>Prefixes</h3>
            <p>Commonly recognised prefixes are used in both modern and Old English to alter the meaning of a base verb in regular ways.
                So, <strong>un-</strong> is used in modern English in much the same way as <strong>on-</strong> was used in Old English - to reverse the meaning of the verb
                it is attached to. This is one way of forming 'new' verbs as well: the verb 'unfriend' uses two Old English roots, but is 
                only attested in the later medieval period: 'unfriend' in the Facebook sense is repurposing a very old term!
            </p>
            <p>Some important prefixes to look out for are <strong>ge-</strong> which intensifies or perfects (emphasises completion of) the 
            action; <strong>be-</strong> which means 'around' or 'about'; and <strong>to-</strong> which often carries the meaning 'break apart'. For example, <em>springan</em> means 'to spring', but <em>tospringan</em> means 'to spring apart or crack', as in this remedy for chapped hands
            '<em>To þæm handum ðæt flæsc tospringaþ - (literally) for hands on which flesh cracks open</em>'.</p>
            
